<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en-GB">
  <!-- @import "../head" -->
  <body>
    <!-- @import "../header" -->

    <main class="article-page">
      <!-- BREADCRUMB -->
      <div class="breadcrumb">
        <span class="tag tag-red-light">DEEP DIVE</span>
        <span class="read-time-badge">8 MIN READ</span>
      </div>

      <!-- ARTICLE TITLE + AUTHOR -->
      <h1>The 12 Font Pairings That Always Work</h1>
      <div class="article-author">
        <img src="../assets/img/gui.avif" alt="Guilherme" class="avatar" />
        <div class="article-author-info">
          <p class="author-name">By Guilherme</p>
          <p class="author-date">Published June 12, 2026</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TWO-COLUMN LAYOUT -->
      <div class="article-layout">
        <!-- MAIN CONTENT COLUMN -->
        <article class="article-content">
          <blockquote class="intro-quote">
            Typography is 95% of design. These 12 editorial pairings have been
            battle-tested across modern SaaS dashboards, e-commerce storefronts,
            and marketing sites — each one downloadable as a ready-to-use Figma
            style reference.
          </blockquote>

          <h2 id="1-saasAndDashboards">1. SaaS & Dashboards</h2>
          <p>
            SaaS interfaces demand clarity above all else. A geometric
            sans-serif for headings paired with a humanist sans for body copy
            creates the right balance of authority and readability. These three
            pairings are used in some of the most recognisable B2B products on
            the market.
          </p>

          <pre class="code-block"><code>/* Pairing 01 — Inter + Inter */
--font-heading: 'Inter', sans-serif;   /* weight 700, tracking -0.02em */
--font-body:    'Inter', sans-serif;   /* weight 400, tracking  0.00em */

/* Pairing 02 — Sora + DM Sans */
--font-heading: 'Sora', sans-serif;    /* weight 600, tracking -0.01em */
--font-body:    'DM Sans', sans-serif; /* weight 400, tracking  0.01em */

/* Pairing 03 — Plus Jakarta Sans + Manrope */
--font-heading: 'Plus Jakarta Sans', sans-serif; /* weight 700 */
--font-body:    'Manrope', sans-serif;            /* weight 400 */</code></pre>

          <h2 id="2-ecommerceAndRetail">2. E-commerce & Retail</h2>
          <p>
            E-commerce sites live or die on trust and desire. A high-contrast
            serif headline evokes premium editorial energy, while a clean sans
            keeps product descriptions scannable. These pairings scale from
            independent boutiques up to global retail brands.
          </p>

          <pre
            class="code-block"
          ><code>/* Pairing 04 — Playfair Display + Lato */
--font-heading: 'Playfair Display', serif; /* weight 700, tracking -0.02em */
--font-body:    'Lato', sans-serif;        /* weight 400 */

/* Pairing 05 — Cormorant Garamond + Source Sans 3 */
--font-heading: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; /* weight 600, tracking 0.03em */
--font-body:    'Source Sans 3', sans-serif; /* weight 400 */

/* Pairing 06 — Fraunces + Nunito Sans */
--font-heading: 'Fraunces', serif;       /* weight 700, optical-size 72 */
--font-body:    'Nunito Sans', sans-serif; /* weight 400 */</code></pre>

          <div class="video-embed">
            <img
              src="../assets/img/video-thumb.jpg"
              alt="Font pairing preview"
            />
          </div>

          <h2 id="3-marketingAndLanding">3. Marketing & Landing Pages</h2>
          <p>
            Marketing pages need to arrest attention in seconds. A display or
            variable font for the hero headline creates a strong visual
            identity, while the body copy stays neutral enough not to compete.
            These pairings are optimised for above-the-fold impact.
          </p>

          <pre
            class="code-block"
          ><code>/* Pairing 07 — Cabinet Grotesk + Satoshi */
--font-heading: 'Cabinet Grotesk', sans-serif; /* weight 800, tracking -0.03em */
--font-body:    'Satoshi', sans-serif;          /* weight 400 */

/* Pairing 08 — Clash Display + General Sans */
--font-heading: 'Clash Display', sans-serif;  /* weight 600, tracking -0.02em */
--font-body:    'General Sans', sans-serif;   /* weight 400 */

/* Pairing 09 — Unbounded + Space Grotesk */
--font-heading: 'Unbounded', sans-serif;      /* weight 700, tracking -0.01em */
--font-body:    'Space Grotesk', sans-serif;  /* weight 400 */</code></pre>

          <blockquote class="pull-quote">
            "The best font pairing is the one where the reader never notices the
            typography — they just feel comfortable and in the right place."
          </blockquote>

          <h2 id="4-editorialAndBlog">4. Editorial & Blog</h2>
          <p>
            Long-form reading requires pairings that sustain attention across
            thousands of words. Opt for fonts with generous x-heights, open
            counters, and subtle optical corrections. These three pairings are
            engineered for readability at 16–18px body size.
          </p>

          <pre
            class="code-block"
          ><code>/* Pairing 10 — Merriweather + Open Sans */
--font-heading: 'Merriweather', serif;  /* weight 700, tracking -0.01em */
--font-body:    'Open Sans', sans-serif; /* weight 400, line-height 1.75 */

/* Pairing 11 — Libre Baskerville + Libre Franklin */
--font-heading: 'Libre Baskerville', serif; /* weight 700 */
--font-body:    'Libre Franklin', sans-serif; /* weight 400, line-height 1.7 */

/* Pairing 12 — Lora + Mulish */
--font-heading: 'Lora', serif;    /* weight 600, tracking 0.01em */
--font-body:    'Mulish', sans-serif; /* weight 400, line-height 1.8 */</code></pre>

          <p>
            Every pairing above is available on Google Fonts at no cost. For
            variable font versions — which let you fine-tune weight and optical
            size as a single file — check the Fontshare and Fonts In Use
            libraries. Always load only the weights you actually use to keep
            page load times under 100ms.
          </p>

          <div class="article-tags">
            <span>Typography</span>
            <span>Figma</span>
            <span>SaaS</span>
            <span>E-commerce</span>
          </div>

          <!-- CTA BANNER -->
          <div class="article-cta">
            <h3>Found this useful?</h3>
            <p>Got a workflow hack of your own? Share it with the community.</p>
            <a href="../contact.html" class="btn btn-light">SUGGEST A TIP →</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- SIDEBAR -->
        <aside class="article-sidebar">
          <!-- TOC Widget -->
          <div class="sidebar-widget">
            <h4 class="sidebar-title">Article Guide</h4>
            <p class="sidebar-label">Quick Navigation</p>
            <nav class="toc">
              <a href="#1-saasAndDashboards" class="toc-active"
                >SaaS & Dashboards</a
              >
              <a href="#2-ecommerceAndRetail" class="toc-link"
                >E-commerce & Retail</a
              >
              <a href="#3-marketingAndLanding" class="toc-link"
                >Marketing & Landing Pages</a
              >
              <a href="#4-editorialAndBlog" class="toc-link"
                >Editorial & Blog</a
              >
            </nav>
          </div>

          <!-- Pro Tip Callout -->
          <div class="sidebar-tip">
            <div class="sidebar-tip-label">
              <span>PRO TIP</span>
            </div>
            <p>
              Keep your type scale to a maximum of two typefaces per project.
              Add contrast through weight and size, not by piling on more font
              families.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Related Resources -->
          <div class="sidebar-related">
            <p class="sidebar-label sidebar-label--spaced">RELATED RESOURCES</p>
            <a
              href="../articles/building-design-system.html"
              class="related-card"
            >
              <p class="related-card-title">
                Building a Design Token System from Scratch
              </p>
              <span class="related-card-link">Read More →</span>
